# SEO & Accessibility Guardrails

## SEO Requirements

### Metadata Standards

Every top route must set:

- **Title**: 40-60 characters, brand-specific
- **Description**: 120-160 characters, action-oriented
- **Canonical URL**: prevent duplicate content
- **Open Graph**: title, description, image, type
- **Twitter Cards**: summary with image

### JSON-LD Schema

- **Games**: VideoGame schema with ratings, genre, platform
- **Products**: Product schema with price, availability, reviews
- **Articles**: Article schema with author, publish date, keywords
- **Organization**: Otaku-mori company data

### Technical SEO

- **Sitemap**: auto-generated with proper priority
- **Robots.txt**: configured for crawling preferences
- **Page Speed**: Core Web Vitals compliance
- **Mobile-first**: responsive design verified

## Accessibility Standards

### WCAG 2.1 AA+ Compliance

- **Color contrast**: minimum 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large
- **Keyboard navigation**: all interactive elements accessible
- **Screen readers**: proper ARIA labels and descriptions
- **Focus management**: visible focus indicators

### Testing Requirements

Add Playwright+Axe scans for:

- `/` (homepage)
- `/mini-games` (GameCube hub)
- `/shop/[slug]` (product pages)
- `/terms` (legal pages)

Build fails on critical a11y violations.

### Implementation Standards

- **Semantic HTML**: proper heading hierarchy, landmarks
- **Form labels**: explicit association with inputs
- **Image alt text**: descriptive for content, empty for decorative
- **Error messaging**: clear, actionable feedback
- **Reduced motion**: respect user preferences

## Validation Tools

### Automated Checks

- **Lighthouse CI**: performance and SEO scores
- **Axe-core**: accessibility violations
- **HTML validation**: semantic correctness
- **Link checking**: no broken internal links

### Manual Testing

- **Screen reader testing**: NVDA/JAWS compatibility
- **Keyboard-only navigation**: complete user flows
- **Mobile usability**: touch targets, viewport
- **Color blindness**: contrast and differentiation
